The '''University of Houston''' (informally referred to as '''UH''') is a public research university located in [[Houston]].  Founded in 1927, it is the oldest and largest institution in the [[University of Houston System]].  UH is the {{nowrap|[[List of largest Texas universities by enrollment|third-largest]]}} university in [[Texas]] with an enrollment of 37,000 students.<ref name="2009 Headcount">{{cite web |url = http://www.uh.edu/ir/fileadmin/reports/factsataglance/Fall_2009_Facts.pdf |title = University of Houston Fall 2009 Facts at a Glance |publisher=University of Houston Office of Institutional Research | accessdate = 2009-10-27 }}</ref>  The institution was formerly known as University of Houston<U+2013>University Park from 1983 to 1991.<ref name="University of Houston<U+2013>University Park"/><ref name="University of Houston"/>

The university serves students in 12 academic colleges and in the interdisciplinary Honors College on a {{convert|667|acre|km2|sing=on}} campus in southeast Houston. UH offers over 316 degree programs: 120 bachelors, 139 masters, 54 doctoral, and three special professional degrees<U+2014>law, optometry, and pharmacy.<ref name="Degree Programs 1">{{cite web |url = http://www.uh.edu/ir/fileadmin/reports/StatisticalHandbook/2009/Degree-Data/Inven%20of%20Degree%20Prog%202009-10_Bachelors.pdf |title = Inventory of Degree Programs: Bachelor Degrees |publisher=University of Houston Office of Institutional Research | accessdate = 2010-05-12 }}</ref><ref name="Degree Programs 2">{{cite web |url = http://www.uh.edu/ir/fileadmin/reports/StatisticalHandbook/2009/Degree-Data/Inven%20of%20Degree%20Prog%202009-10_Masters.pdf |title = Inventory of Degree Programs: Master Degrees |publisher=University of Houston Office of Institutional Research | accessdate = 2010-05-12 }}</ref><ref name="Degree Programs 3">{{cite web |url = http://www.uh.edu/ir/fileadmin/reports/StatisticalHandbook/2009/Degree-Data/Inven%20of%20Degree%20Prog%202009-10_Doctoral.pdf |title = Inventory of Degree Programs: Doctoral Degrees |publisher=University of Houston Office of Institutional Research | accessdate = 2010-05-12 }}</ref><ref name="Degree Programs 4">{{cite web |url = http://www.uh.edu/ir/fileadmin/reports/StatisticalHandbook/2009/Degree-Data/Inven%20of%20Degree%20Prog%202009-10_SPECIAL%20PROFESIONAL.pdf |title = Inventory of Degree Programs: Special Professional Degrees |publisher=University of Houston Office of Institutional Research | accessdate = 2010-05-12 }}</ref>  Awarding more than 7,100 degrees annually, the university's alumni base is the largest in the Houston area.<ref name="UH at a Glance">{{cite web |url = http://www.uh.edu/ir/fileadmin/reports/factsataglance/Fall_2008_Facts.pdf |title = University of Houston Fall 2008 Facts at a Glance |publisher=University of Houston Office of Institutional Research | accessdate = 2008-12-25 }}</ref>  Also known for its diverse student population, it perennially ranks as the second most ethnically diverse national university in the country by ''U.S. News and World Report''.

The University of Houston conducts [[research]] in each academic department and operates more than 40 research centers and institutes on campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uh.edu/research/labs-center |title=Research Centers & Institutes |publisher=University of Houston |accessdate=2008-03-23}}</ref> Interdisciplinary research conducted at UH includes [[superconductivity]], space commercialization, [[biomedical engineering]], economics, education, petroleum exploration, and virtual technology.

The university hosts a variety of theatrical performances, concerts, lectures, and intercollegiate athletic events.  Its varsity athletics teams&mdash;known as the [[Houston Cougars]]&mdash;are members of [[Conference USA]] and compete in the [[NCAA|NCAA's]] [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] in all sports .  The football team regularly makes bowl game appearances, and the men's basketball team has made sixteen appearances in the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|NCAA Division I Tournament]], including five [[Final Four]] appearances.  The men's golf team has won sixteen [[NCAA Division I Men's Golf Championships|national championships]], the second most of any NCAA golf program.

==History==
===Founding===
[[Image:University of Houston in 1934.jpg|thumb|The University of Houston administrative offices at [[San Jacinto High School]] in 1934]] 
The University of Houston began as Houston Junior College (HJC).  On March 7, 1927, trustees of the [[Houston Independent School District]] [[Board of Education]] unanimously passed a resolution that authorized the founding and operating of a junior college.  The junior college was operated and controlled by the [[Houston Independent School District]] (HISD).<ref name="Handbook of Texas">{{cite web |url=http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/UU/kcu3.html |title=University of Houston<U+2013>University Park |publisher=Texas State Historical Association |work=Hand book of Texas |accessdate=2007-10-16}}</ref><ref name="Homecoming 2007 Timeline">{{cite web |url=http://www.advancement.uh.edu/homecoming/2007/timeline.htm |title=UH Timeline |publisher=University of Houston |accessdate=2007-10-16}}</ref>

Originally HJC was located in [[San Jacinto High School]] and offered only night courses.<ref name="UH Through Time: Events">{{cite web |url=http://info.lib.uh.edu/sca/digital/time/events.html |title=UH Through Time: Events |publisher=University of Houston Libraries |accessdate=2007-10-16}}</ref>  Its first session began March 7, 1927, with an enrollment of 232 students and 12 faculty.<ref name="Handbook of Texas" />  This session was primarily held to educate the future teachers of the junior college, and no freshmen were allowed to enroll.  A more accurate date for the official opening of HJC is September 19, 1927, when enrollment was opened to all persons having completed the necessary educational requirements.<ref name="Roarin 07">{{cite web |url=http://www.mycougarconnection.com/homecoming/history.htm |title=Discover UH's Heritage & History |publisher=UH Alumni Organization |accessdate=2007-10-16}}</ref>  The first president of HJC was [[Edison E. Oberholtzer|Edison Ellsworth Oberholtzer]], who was the dominant force in establishing the [[junior college]].<ref name="Handbook of Texas" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/OO/fob2.html |work=Handbook of Texas |title=Oberholtzer, Edison, Ellsworth |publisher=Texas State Historical Association |accessdate=2008-04-06}}</ref>

===University beginnings===
The junior college became eligible to become a [[university|four-year institution]] in October 1933 when Governor [[Miriam A. Ferguson]] signed House Bill 194 into law.  On April 30, 1934, HISD's Board of Education adopted a resolution to make the school a four-year institution, and Houston Junior College became the University of Houston.<ref name="Roarin 07" />

[[Image:University of Houston in 1940.jpg|left|thumb|The University of Houston campus in 1940 at its present location]]
UH's first session as a four-year institution began June 4, 1934, at San Jacinto High School with an enrollment of 682. In 1934, the first campus of the University of Houston was established at the Second Baptist Church at Milam and McGowen.  The next fall, the campus was moved to the [[South Main Baptist Church]], on Main between Richmond and Eagle, where it stayed for the next five years.<ref name="Roarin 07" />

[[Image:Roy G. Cullen Memorial building preliminary drawing.jpg|thumb|A preliminary drawing of the [[Roy G. Cullen Memorial building]] by its architect in 1938]]
In 1936, philanthropists Julius Settegast and [[Ben Taub]] donated {{convert|110|acre|km2}} to the university for use as a permanent location.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/first100/869592.html |title="Group of average students sparks UH creation" |date=2001-04-08 |accessdate=2008-04-06 |publisher=''[[Houston Chronicle]]''}}</ref> Two years later, [[Hugh Roy Cullen]] donated $335,000 for the first building to be built at the location.  The [[Roy G. Cullen Memorial Building|Roy Gustav Cullen Memorial Building]], was dedicated on June 4, 1939, and classes began the next day.  The first full semester of classes began officially on Wednesday, September 20, 1939.<ref name="Roarin 07" />

On March 12, 1945, Senate Bill 207 was signed into law, removing the control of the University of Houston from HISD and placing it into the hands of a board of regents.<ref name="Roarin 07" /> In 1945, the university, which had grown too large and complex for the Houston school board to administer, became a private university. In March 1947, the regents authorized creation of a law school at the university, initially designated as the Bates College of Law but later renamed the [[University of Houston Law Center]]. In 1949, the M. D. Anderson Foundation made a $1.5 million gift to UH for the construction of a dedicated library building on the campus. By 1950, the educational plant at UH consisted of 12 permanent buildings. Enrollment was more than 14,000 with a full-time faculty of more than 300.<ref name="Handbook of Texas" />  By 1951, UH was the second-largest university in the State of Texas and was the fastest growing university in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,815555,00.html |title=Archangel in Houston |date=1951-10-15 |publisher=Time Magazine |accessdate=2009-02-22}}</ref>

===State university===
[[Image:UH Religion Center.jpg|thumb|left|The [[A.D. Bruce]] Religion Center was named after the former President of UH]]
In 1953, the university established [[KUHT]], the first educational [[television]] station in the nation.<ref name="Handbook of Texas" /> During this period, however, the university as a private institution was facing financial troubles. Tuition failed to cover rising costs, and in turn, tuition increases caused a drop in enrollment. After a lengthy battle between supporters of the University of Houston, led by school president [[A.D. Bruce]],<ref name="txarchives">{{cite web |url=http://www.lib.utexas.edu/taro/uhua/00001/hua-00001.html |title=A.D. Bruce Speeches Collection, 1954-1961 |publisher=University of Texas Libraries |work=Texas Archival Resources Online (TARO) |accessdate=2007-06-25}}</ref> and forces from [[State university system|state universities]] geared to block the change, Senate Bill 2 was passed on May 23, 1961, enabling the university to enter the state system in 1963.<ref name="Handbook of Texas" />

In 1977, the [[University of Houston System]] was established, with the University of Houston named as the flagship institution of the system.<ref name="UH at a Glance" />  The University of Houston appended its official name to "University of Houston<U+2013>University Park" in April 1983.<ref name="University of Houston<U+2013>University Park">{{cite book|last=Adair|first=Wendy|title=The University of Houston: Our Time: Celebrating 75 Years of Learning and Leading|year=2001|publisher=Donning Company Publishers|location= |isbn=978-1-57864-143-7}}</ref> This name change was an effort by the University of Houston System to give its flagship institution a distinctive name that would eliminate confusion with the other three UHS universities. While these three universities ([[University of Houston<U+2013>Clear Lake|UH<U+2013>Clear Lake]], [[University of Houston<U+2013>Downtown|UH<U+2013>Downtown]], and [[University of Houston<U+2013>Victoria|UH<U+2013>Victoria]]) share the root name "University of Houston," they are essentially autonomous institutions, and each has its own president.  By August 1991, the flagship institution reverted to its original name of "University of Houston" after controversy and general resistance within the university community regarding the name change.<ref name="University of Houston<U+2013>University Park"/><ref name="University of Houston">{{cite web |url=http://www.legis.state.tx.us/billlookup/History.aspx?LegSess=72R&Bill=SB755|title=72(R) History for Senate Bill 755|publisher=Texas Legislature|work=Texas Legislature Online History |accessdate=2010-03-28}}</ref>

===Merger of UH and UH System administrations===
[[Image:University of Houston Fall Enrollment.png|thumb|Fall enrollment trend at the University of Houston (1927-2007)]]
In 1997, the UH System and the University of Houston administrations merged into a single governing entity. Arthur K. Smith, then the UH president, became the first person to hold both the UH System chancellorship and University of Houston presidency simultaneously. Smith was responsible for overseeing the successful merger of the UH System and UH administrations, the launching of the "Learning. Leading." image campaign, the planning and construction of major buildings at all UH System institutions, a growth in external funding for research, and an increase in student enrollment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uh.edu/admin/media/newsroom/announcement/presidents1.html |title=University of Houston Presidents |publisher=University of Houston System |accessdate=2007-10-16}}</ref>

As of the merger in 1997, the University of Houston System administration is located in the [[Ezekiel W. Cullen Building]] on the University of Houston campus. On June 1, 2007, former UH President and Chancellor Dr. [[Jay Gogue]] left UH and UH System to become President of [[Auburn University]]. The University of Houston System Board of Regents appointed John M. Rudley, vice chancellor/vice president for administration and finance, to serve as Interim UH System Chancellor and Interim UH President.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uh.edu/admin/media/nr/2007/05may/051707johnrudleyinterimleader.html |title=John Rudley Named as Interim Leader of UH and UH System |publisher=University of Houston |accessdate=2007-10-16}}</ref>

On October 15, 2007, [[Renu Khator|Dr. Renu Khator]]&mdash;who had served as provost and senior vice president of the [[University of South Florida]]&mdash;was selected for the position of UH System chancellor and UH president.<ref name="Noted Political Science Scholar">{{cite web |title="Scholar and Administrator Selected as Sole Nominee" 
|work=UH News Release |url=http://www.uh.edu/news-events/archive/nr/2007/10oct/101507khator.html |accessdate=2007-05-11}}</ref> On November 5, 2007, Khator was confirmed as the third person to hold the UH System chancellor and UH president position simultaneously, and took her position in January 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uh.edu/news-events/newsrelease.php?releaseid_int=76 |title="Renu Khator Confirmed as New University of Houston & UH System Leader" |author=Gerber, Eric |publisher=University of Houston |accessdate=2007-11-27}}</ref>

==Academics==
[[Image:UH Architecture Building.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Hines College of Architecture]] building was designed by [[Philip Johnson]] in 1985.]]
The mission of the University of Houston is to "provide a range of educational programs that foster an intellectually and culturally diverse environment that enhances individual growth and development."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uh.edu/admin/mission.html |title=Mission |publisher=University of Houston |accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>

The university offers over 316 degree programs: 120 bachelors, 139 masters, 54 doctoral, and three special professional degrees<U+2014>law, optometry, and pharmacy.<ref name="Degree Programs 1" /><ref name="Degree Programs 2" /><ref name="Degree Programs 3" /><ref name="Degree Programs 4" />  In fiscal year 2004, the university conducted more than $75.9 million in research programs and ranked third in research expenditures within Texas when compared to non-medical institutions, and eighth when medical institutions were also considered.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecb.state.tx.us/reports/PDF/0836.PDF |title=Research Expenditures |publisher=Texas Higher Education Coordinating Board |accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>

The University of Houston's academic colleges are as follows:

