===Faculty and research===
The University of Houston conducts research in each academic department and operates more than 40 research centers and institutes on campus. Through these facilities, UH maintains creative partnerships with government, health care and private industry.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Methodist Neurological Institute, University of Houston combine 'brain power' | work = Focus on ALS | accessdate = 2009-04-01 | url = http://www.focusonals.com/university_combine.htm}}</ref> Areas of interdisciplinary research conducted at UH include [[superconductivity]], space commercialization, [[biomedical engineering]], economics, education, petroleum exploration, and virtual technology.

The University of Houston's faculty includes three-time [[Pulitzer Prize]] winner [[Edward Albee]], [[National Medal of Science]] recipient [[Paul C. W. Chu|Paul Chu]], and [[Nobel Peace Prize]] Laureate [[Jody Williams]].  The University's College of Liberal Arts and Social Sciences is home to the [[University of Houston Creative Writing Program|Creative Writing Program]], which was founded by alumnus [[Donald Barthelme]] and offers M.F.A. and Ph.D. degrees in poetry, fiction, and non-fiction. Noted writers who have emerged from the program include novelists [[Robert Clark Young]] and [[Padgett Powell]]. The program attracts major authors, including international and award-winning authors. The Creative Writing Program was ranked second in the nation by ''U.S. News & World Report'' in its first annual ranking of writing programs in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.class.uh.edu/cwp/ |title=Welcome to the Fall semester 2007 |publisher=UH Creative Writing Program |accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>

===Rankings===
[[Image:Front of M.D. Anderson Library.jpg|thumb|M. D. Anderson Memorial Library, the largest of the [[University of Houston Libraries]]]]
The University of Houston is ranked second among national universities for Campus Ethnic Diversity by ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''.<ref name="Diversity ranking">{{cite web |url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/national-campus-ethnic-diversity |title=Best Colleges: Racial Diversity: National Universities |publisher=U.S. News & World Report |accessdate=2010-03-27}}</ref>  It also ranks the [[Bauer College of Business]] as the top Undergraduate Business Program in Houston, third among public universities in the state of Texas, and 63rd in the nation among public universities.  The ranking places the Bauer College in the top quartile of the approximately 400 [[AACSB]]-accredited undergraduate business programs and top five percent among all 1608 undergraduate business programs in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bauer.uh.edu/downloads/2007_Bauer_At_A_Glance.pdf |title=Bauer College of Business: At a Glance |publisher=Bauer College of Business |accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref> It has been ranked the best entrepreneurship program by the Princeton Review.<ref>[http://www.princetonreview.com/undergraduate-entrepreneurial-programs.aspx http://www.princetonreview.com/undergraduate-entrepreneurial-programs.aspx]</ref>

The evening [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] program was ranked as the 27th best part-time MBA program in the country by ''[[Businessweek]]'' in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bwnt.businessweek.com/interactive_reports/bschool_ptmba_2007/ |title=The Best Part-Time MBA Programs |publisher=Businessweek |accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref> It also ranks 5th among public universities for producing [[CEO]]s of [[S&P 500]] companies, according to ''Bloomberg Markets''. Houston was tied with the University of Michigan and Dartmouth.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bauer.uh.edu/mba/ |title=How we rank |publisher=Bauer College of Business |accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>  The EMBA Program ranked 17th in the U.S. among public EMBA programs according to the 2004 ''[[Financial Times]]'' ranking of the top 75 EMBA Programs in the World.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rankings.ft.com/rankings/emba/rankings.html |title=EMBA rankings |publisher=Financial Times |work=FT.com |accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>

Additionally, the college's Entrepreneurship program ranked number 1 in the nation by ''The Princeton Review'' and ''Entrepreneur'' magazine in 2008, up from number 2 in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uh.edu/news-events/archive/nr/2007/10oct/101007bauer_ranking.html |title="Bauer College at University of Houston Entrepreneurship Program Lands on Top of Prestigious National List" |publisher=University of Houston |date=2007-10-10 |accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref>

The [[University of Houston Law Center]] is a Tier I law school, currently ranked 60th in the nation by ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/items/03154 2010 |title=University of Houston |publisher=U.S. News & World Report |accessdate=2010-04-17}}</ref>  In addition, the news magazine ranks three of the Law Center's specialty programs in the top ten in the country: the Health Law and Policy Institute (Healthcare Law), the Institute for Intellectual Property and Information Law (IP Law), and the Blakely Advocacy Institute (Trial Advocacy).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/usnews/edu/grad/rankings/law/lawindex_brief.php |title=2008 Law Specialties Rankings |publisher=U.S. News & World Report |accessdate=2007-11-24}}</ref>

The [[Hines College of Architecture]] is one of only 36 schools to have an accreditation certificate from the [[National Architectural Accrediting Board|NAAB]] for both Bachelor's and Master's Degree programs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.naab.org/usr_doc/Accredited_Programs_22.pdf |title=Accredited and Candidate Programs in Architecture |publisher=[[National Architectural Accrediting Board|NAAB]] |accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>  It recently added an [[industrial design]] program, the first in the state of Texas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arch.uh.edu/prog/BSI.html |title=Undergraduate Programs: Industrial Design |publisher=Hines College of Architecture |accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>  In 2002, the [[Hilton College of Hotel and Restaurant Management]] ranked third in the nation in hospitality management by the Journal of Hospitality & Tourism Education.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.uns.purdue.edu/html3month/020710.Kavanaugh.rank2002.html |title="Purdue tops national survey of hospitality management programs" |author=Lillich, J.M. |publisher=Purdue University |accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>  Additionally, according to the [[Institute for Scientific Information]], five of the top fifty cited physicists in the world come from the university's [[University of Houston College of Natural Sciences and Mathematics|College of Natural Sciences and Mathematics]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uhcougars.cstv.com/school-bio/hou-school-bio-university.html |title=UH Athletics: On Campus] |publisher=UH Athletics |accessdate=2007-10-04}}</ref>

==Campus==
{{wide image|cullen_plaza.jpg|1000px|alt=The Cullen Family Plaza, a central area on campus where many of the first buildings were built.|The Cullen Family Plaza, a central area on campus where many of the first buildings were built}}

The University of Houston (formerly University of Houston<U+2013>University Park) is a single-campus university located in southeast Houston, with an official address of 4800 Calhoun Road.  The campus spans {{convert|667|acre|km2|sing=on}} and is roughly bisected by [[Cullen Boulevard]]&mdash;a thoroughfare that has become synonymous with the university.

The university campus includes numerous green spaces, fountains, and sculptures, including a work by famed sculptor [[Jim Sanborn]].  Renowned architects [[C<U+00E9>sar Pelli]] and [[Philip Johnson]] have designed buildings on the UH campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uh.edu/uhtoday/2004/06jun/062804sanborn.html |title="Art that Speaks for Itself Enlightens New Sculpture" |author=Vasquez, Leticia |publisher=University of Houston |work=UH Today |accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>  Recent campus beautification projects have garnered awards from the Keep Houston Beautiful group for improvements made to the Cullen&nbsp;Boulevard corridor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uh.edu/uhtoday/2005/12dec/121505keephoustonbeautiful.html |title="UH Keeps Houston Beautiful" |author=Parker, Francine |publisher=University of Houston |work=UH Today |accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>

===Facilities===
The LeRoy and Lucile Melcher Center for Public Broadcasting houses the studios and offices of [[KUHT]]-TV Houston [[PBS]], the nation's first public television station;<ref>{{Cite web | title = Appreciation for KUHT, Houston Public Television | work = Resolution of the Board of Directors, Corporation for Public Broadcasting | date = 1993-05-24 | accessdate = 2009-04-08| url = http://www.cpb.org/aboutcpb/leadership/board/resolutions/resolution.php?prn=807}}</ref> [[KUHF]] (88.7 FM), Houston's [[NPR]] station; the Center for Public Policy Polling; and television studio labs.
[[Image:Lyndall Finley Wortham Theatre.jpg|thumb|Wortham Theatre]]
The [[Blaffer Gallery]] exhibits the works of both visiting artists and those of students in the [[University of Houston School of Art]].  The campus also has the [[Cynthia Woods Mitchell Center for the Performing Arts]] which houses the Lyndall Finley Wortham Theatre and Moores Opera Center.

[[Image:UH Recreation and Wellness Center.jpg|thumb|left|Campus Recreation and Wellness Center]]
The 264,000&nbsp;ft<U+00B2> (25,000 m<U+00B2>) Campus Recreation and Wellness Center, which is home to the nation's largest collegiate natatorium, was recognized by the National Intramural-Sports Association as an outstanding facility upon its completion in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nirsa.org/about/awards/awards_04.htm |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20040617024931/http://www.nirsa.org/about/awards/awards_04.htm |title=NIRSA Awards |publisher=National Intramural-Recreational Sports Association |accessdate=2007-10-12 |archivedate=2004-06-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thedailycougar.com/static/vol70/19/news/news2.html |publisher=''The Daily Cougar'' |title="CRWC wins national award" |author=Kastendieck, Todd |accessdate=2008-03-18}}</ref>  The venues for most UH varsity athletic teams are located on the campus, including [[Hofheinz Pavilion]], [[Robertson Stadium]], and [[Cougar Field]].  The athletic facilities are situated in a contiguous block of land between [[Cullen Boulevard]] and Scott Street, with the exception of the Campus Recreation and Wellness Center.

The {{convert|200000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} Science and Engineering Research and Classroom Complex (SERCC) was designed by architect [[C<U+00E9>sar Pelli]].<ref>[http://www.pcparch.com/textOnly/projects.cfm#81 Pelli Clarke Pelli Projects]. Pelli Clarke Pelli Architects official site. Retrieved 12 October 2007.</ref> It houses facilities for many interdisciplinary research programs at UH including [[bionanotechnology]].  The university has an on-campus [[Hilton Hotels|Hilton]] hotel that is part of the [[Hilton College of Hotel and Restaurant Management]].  This hotel was established with a donation by the founder of [[Hilton Hotels Corporation|Hilton Hotels]], [[Conrad N. Hilton]], and is staffed by students in the College of Hotel and Restaurant Management.
[[Image:UH Hilton Hotel.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Hilton Hotel]] University of Houston, the university's on-campus hotel, also contains the [[Hilton College of Hotel and Restaurant Management]]]]

===Parking and transit===
In addition to parking facilities including garages and lots for [[Commuting|commuters]], public transportation is available to and from the University of Houston via several [[Metropolitan Transit Authority of Harris County, Texas|METRO]] bus routes.  UH operates an air-conditioned [[Bus|shuttle bus]] service that is free to anyone with a university identification card.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://houston.about.com/od/universities/ss/UHTour.htm |title=''University of Houston Tour: First Stop: Get on the Bus!'' |author=Davenport, Melinda |publisher=About.com |accessdate=2007-10-06}}</ref>

==Student life==
===Demographics===
The University of Houston is notable for its diverse student body, and ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranks UH as the second-most diverse research university in the United States.<ref name="Diversity ranking" /> With 37,000 students, the university has significant [[Asian American]] and [[Hispanic]] populations. Its international student population is primarily from Asia.<ref name="UH at a Glance" />  As of fall 2006, the demographic makeup of the student population was 38.5 percent non-Hispanic white, 19.5 percent Asian or Pacific Islander, 19.3 percent Hispanic (of any race), 13.2 percent non-Hispanic black, 0.4 percent American Indian or Alaskan Native, 7.3 percent International (regardless of race), and 1.8 percent other or unknown.<ref name="UH at a Glance" />

===Housing===
[[Image:UH Moody Towers.jpg|thumb|left|Moody Towers, UH's largest complex of residential halls]]
Twelve percent of UH students live on campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uh.edu/uhtoday/2007/08aug/080607newparkinggarage_rvote.html |author=Emery, Mike |title="Regents to Vote on New Parking Garage" |publisher=UH Office of Internal Commuications |date=2007-08-06 |accessdate=2008-04-07}}</ref> UH has two main housing areas for dormitories: Moody Towers and the Quadrangle.  Moody Towers, frequently just called "The Towers", is one of the tallest complexes on campus and the largest area of residence halls.  Each of the two towers consists of eighteen stories and together house 1,100 students.  The Quadrangle, also known as "The Quad" is the oldest housing area on campus and consists of several coed dorm halls:  Bates, Law, Oberholtzer, Settegast, and Taub.  The Quadrangle houses 800 students.<ref name="Housing">{{cite web |url=http://www.housing.uh.edu/housingmain.html |title=Housing Areas |publisher=UH Residential Life & Housing |accessdate=2007-10-01}}</ref>  In addition to traditional dormitories, UH has an apartment-style dormitory called Cougar Place that is a housing area consisting of 400 units.<ref name="Housing" />

UH also has several privately-owned apartment complexes on campus that are Cullen Oaks, Bayou Oaks, and Cambridge Oaks.  In August 2009 Calhoun Lofts, a new university-owned and operated residential facility aimed at graduate and professional students opened and includes retail stores, lecture halls, and recreation facilities.

Cougar Village, a new freshman dorm is expected to open for the Fall 2010 semester. This dormitory will feature themed floors, a convenience store, laundry facility, and a fitness center.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uh.edu/dsa/student_lofts.html |title=Student Lofts |publisher=UH Division of Student Affairs |accessdate=2007-10-01}}</ref>

===Media and entertainment===
[[File:Melcher Center for Public Broadcasting.jpg|thumb|right|LeRoy and Lucile Melcher Center for Public Broadcasting]]
The official student newspaper is ''[[The Daily Cougar]]'', and has been published since 1927.<ref name="Roarin 07" />  Students also produce the official University of Houston yearbook, ''The Houstonian''.

The University of Houston operates a public television station, [[KUHT]], and public radio station, [[KUHF]]. Both stations are licensed to the University. KUHT (Channel 8) is a [[PBS]] member station and the first public television station in the United States, and KUHF (88.7 FM) is an [[National Public Radio|NPR]] member station. Both stations broadcast on campus from the LeRoy and Lucile Melcher Center for Public Broadcasting.  

The [[University of Houston Student Video Network|UH Student Video Network]], a student-run network, appears on the University of Houston cable network and is one of the few fee-funded student organizations on campus.
{{-}}
==Traditions==
[[Image:University of Houston.png|94px|thumb|left|Official collegiate symbol]]
[[Image:UH Male Cougar Sculpture.jpg|thumb|right|Cougar sculpture near the entrance of the [[E. Cullen Building]] by Alaska-based R.T. <U+201C>Skip<U+201D> Wallen]]
Cougar First Impressions, a program headed by the UH Staff Council, takes place every year on the first two days of classes, when faculty and staff turn out to welcome new and returning students.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uh.edu/sc/cfi/ |title=Cougar First Impressions |publisher=UH Staff Council |accessdate=2007-10-16}}</ref>  [[Frontier Fiesta]], a re-creation of a 19th-century [[Western United States|Western]] town, with music, food and historical exhibits, is a major event on campus each spring semester. The student led festival is a part of a long-standing tradition at UH dating back to the 1940s.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Fiesta fun in full swing | work = The Daily Cougar | author = Allison Smith
| date = 2009-03-26 | accessdate = 2009-04-08| url = http://www.thedailycougar.com/fiesta-fun-in-full-swing-1.1629919}}</ref>

The official colors of the University of Houston are scarlet red and albino white.  These were the colors of [[Sam Houston]]'s ancestor<U+2014>Sir Hugh<U+2014>and were adopted by UH at the same time as the official seal.  Scarlet red symbolizes courage or inner strength to face the unknown, and white symbolizes the goodness and purity of spirit embodied in helping one's fellow man.  The seal of the University of Houston, officially adopted in 1938, is a stylized version of the coat-of-arms of General [[Sam Houston]].  The first official version was placed on the floor of the [[Roy Gustav Cullen Building]].<ref name="Traditions">{{cite web |url=http://uhcougars.cstv.com/trads/hou-trads.html |title=University of Houston Traditions |publisher=UH Athletics |accessdate=2007-10-16}}</ref>

The school's official mascot is a [[cougar]], which was adopted in 1947 and later named [[Shasta (mascot)|Shasta]].<ref>[http://uh.edu/about/history/index.php http://uh.edu/about/history/index.php]</ref> The university had a live cougar, but the tradition ended in 1989.

The [[Frontiersmen (University of Houston)|Frontiersmen]] are a group of students who participate in university events to drive school spirit.  At football games, the Frontiersmen<U+2014>donning [[cowboy hat]]s, [[Wrangler Jeans]], and [[Duster (clothing)|dusters]] for attire<U+2014>run across the field with the university's flag and the [[Flag of Texas]] after each score.

===The Cougar Paw===
[[Image:UoHcougarpaw.png|thumb|95px|Graphic representation of The Cougar Paw]]
The Cougar Paw is a popular [[Manual communication|hand sign]] used by University of Houston students, faculty, alumni, and athletics fans to represent camaraderie and support.  The Cougar Paw tradition was adopted through several athletics events between the University of Houston and [[University of Texas at Austin|The University of Texas]]. The first time UH played UT in [[American football|football]] was in 1953, and since this was their first meeting, members of [[Alpha Phi Omega]], the service [[fraternities and sororities|fraternity]] in charge of taking care of [[Shasta (mascot)#Shasta I|Shasta I]], the university's [[mascot]], brought her to the game.  During the trip, Shasta's front paw was caught in the cage door and one toe was cut off.  At the game, members of the opposing team discovered what had happened and began taunting UH players by holding up their hands with the ring finger bent.  UT went on to win this game 28<U+2013>7, and UH students began using the sign as notice that they would remember the taunts.  In 1968, at their second meeting, the Cougars, holding up the now-adopted symbol of UH pride, played UT to a 20<U+2013>20 tie. UH did not play UT again until 1976, the first year UH was a member of the [[Southwest Conference]].  In front of a record crowd, UH defeated UT 30<U+2013>0.  This solidified the use of the Cougar Paw as a tradition.<ref name="Traditions" />

==UH in popular culture==
The 1996 film ''[[Tin Cup]]'' depicts [[Kevin Costner]]'s and [[Don Johnson]]'s characters as former teammates on the University of Houston [[Houston Cougars men's golf|golf team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19960816/REVIEWS/608160305/1023 |title=Tin Cup |author=Ebert, Roger |work=rogerebert.com |accessdate=2007-11-27}}</ref>  The film featured several real-life UH alumni and former men's golf team members, including [[Fred Couples]], [[Steve Elkington]], and [[Bruce Lietzke]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://movies.warnerbros.com/tincup/cmp/profiles.html |title=Tin Cup PGA Player Profiles |publisher=Warner Bros. Entertainment, Inc. |accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref>  The 1999 film ''[[Arlington Road]]'' was partially filmed on-campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amazon.com/dp/B00004SAI1 |title=Arlington Road (1999) |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=2007-11-27}}</ref>  [[Jeff Bridges]]' character and his girlfriend are seen walking between Melcher Hall and the University Center.  Other locations on campus are the inside of a classroom in Agnes Arnold Hall and a telephone booth in the [[University of Houston College of Technology|College of Technology]] Annex.  Also filmed on campus was the 2003 movie ''[[Dude, Where's the Party?]]'', where [[Kal Penn]]'s character attends the university.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0306228/locations |title=Where's the Party, Yaar? (2003) - Filming locations |publisher=The Internet Movie Database |accessdate=2007-11-28}}</ref>

In the long-running television show [[Reba (TV series)|''Reba'']], [[Steve Howey (actor)|Steve Howey's]] character, Van, receives a scholarship to play as a cornerback for the [[Houston Cougars football]] team in the episode "Labor for Love."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tv.com//labor-of-love/episode/119941/summary.html?q=&tag=search_results;episode_title;3 |title=Reba:  Labor of Love |publisher=TV.com |accessdate=2007-11-27}}</ref>  In a later episode, "Skating Away," Van, his wife, Cheyenne, and their new baby move into an on-campus apartment at the university while Van plays football.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tv.com//skating-away/episode/184871/summary.html?q=&tag=search_results;episode_title;2 |title=Reba:  Skating Away |publisher=TV.com |accessdate=2007-11-27}}</ref>

In the 1999 movie ''[[Any Given Sunday]]'', [[Jamie Foxx]]'s character was portrayed as a former football player of the University of Houston.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cswap.com/1999/Any_Given_Sunday/cap/en/2_Parts/a/00_05 |title=Any Given Sunday |author=Caption Swap |work=cswap.com |accessdate=2008-11-25}}</ref>

==Athletics==
{{main|Houston Cougars}}
[[Image:University of Houston Logo.svg|thumb|140px|left|UH Athletics logo]]
UH's 16-sport intercollegiate program is a member of [[Conference USA]]. Since the conference was formed in 1995, the Cougars have won 33 C-USA titles.  After 61 years of athletics at UH, other notable achievements include 16 national titles in [[Houston Cougars men's golf|men's golf]], five NCAA Men's Basketball [[Final Four]] appearances, and two [[College World Series]] appearances.

More than 50 Olympic athletes have attended UH, bringing home 33 medals, including 19 gold.<ref name="UH at a Glance" /> Former Olympian and UH alumnus [[Leroy Burrell]] returned as the men's [[track and field]] head coach in 1998, while in March 2004, [[Tom Penders]] was named the seventh men's basketball head coach.  In December 2007, [[Kevin Sumlin]] was introduced as the university's twelfth head football coach.

In addition to varsity sports, the University of Houston offers a variety of [[intramural sport]]s programs.

===Varsity sports===
[[Image:2008 UH Cougars vs Air Force Falcons.jpg|thumb|The [[Houston Cougars football]] team]]
The university has an intercollegiate sports program that competes in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]. The NCAA's [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] sports at the University of Houston include [[baseball]], [[basketball]], cross country, [[American football]], [[golf]], and [[track and field]] for men; [[basketball]], cross country, [[soccer]], [[softball]], swimming and diving, [[tennis]], and [[track and field]] for women. 

The [[Houston Cougars football|football]] team has made 16 post-season bowl appearances and has to its credit several [[Southwest Conference]] championships and [[Cotton Bowl Classic]] appearances, as well as the 2006 [[Conference USA]] Championship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uhcougars.cstv.com/trads/hou-trads-liberty.html |title=Cougars Bowl Game Trivia |publisher=UH Athletics |accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>  The 1989 Heisman Trophy winner, [[Andre Ware]], was a Cougar.  The varsity football team went 8-5 in 2008, including a 34-28 win against the [[2008 Air Force Falcons football team|Air Force Falcons]] in the [[2008 Armed Forces Bowl|Armed Forces Bowl]] on December 31, 2008.

The [[Houston Cougars men's basketball|men's basketball]] team has made 18 [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|NCAA Tournament]] appearances, with five trips to the Final Four. See also [[Phi Slama Jama]], the Cougars teams of the early 1980s that featured current [[Basketball Hall of Fame]]rs [[Clyde Drexler]] and [[Hakeem Olajuwon]].

Houston competes with other notable sports teams, such as the [[Houston Cougars baseball|baseball]] team, which has made 18 NCAA Tournament appearances with two trips to the College World Series; the [[Houston Cougars men's golf|men's golf]] team, which has won 16 NCAA National Championships; the women's [[soccer]] team, was rated as the top first-year women's program in the country in 1998; the [[swimming (sport)|swimming]] and [[diving]] teams, which have spawned multiple Olympians and [[All-America]]ns; the [[track and field]] team, which perennially ranks in the top 10 as an NCAA team; and the [[volleyball]] team, which had a streak of ten consecutive trips to the NCAA Tournament.

==Notable people==
{{main|List of University of Houston people}}
With strong academic programs in the arts, media, business, hospitality management, law, as well as a successful athletics program, the University of Houston has seen many now notable persons pass through its halls.  [[Jack Valenti]], long-time president of the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] and creator of the [[MPAA film rating system]], received his B.B.A. from UH and for decades was one of the most influential people in [[Hollywood]]. Acclaimed artist and filmmaker [[Julian Schnabel]] is also a University of Houston alum.  [[Elizabeth Warren]], a Harvard Law School faculty member and chair of the Congressional Oversight Panel created to oversee the U.S. banking bailout during the 2008-2009 financial crisis, received her B.S. from UH in 1970. [[Alice Sebold]] a well known and favored American Novelist, publishing one of America's Best sellers; including Lucky and The Lovely Bones.

Notable athletes within the list include NFL players  [[Wilson Whitley]], [[Glenn Montgomery]], [[Alfred Oglesby]], [[Craig Veasey]], [[Donnie Avery]], [[David Klingler]], [[Kevin Kolb]], and Heisman Trophy winner [[Andre Ware]]; golfer [[Fred Couples]]; track and field legend [[Carl Lewis]]; the NBA's [[Bo Outlaw]], [[Clyde Drexler]], [[Elvin Hayes]], [[Hakeem Olajuwon]] and [[Carl Herrera]]; and legendary [[Dallas Cowboys]] coach [[Tom Landry]].

==Alumni==
The University of Houston Alumni Association (UHAA) is the official [[alumni association]] of the University of Houston.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl?id=1993_1129730 |title=UH Athletics at a Crossroads |author=Feigen, Jonathan |coauthors=Wizig, Jerry |date=1993-05-16 |publisher=''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' |accessdate=2009-07-16}}</ref>  Formed in 1940, UHAA is a [[non-profit organization]] with a membership of over 18,000 dues-paying members.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alumniconnections.com/olc/pub/UHU/about/about_1.html |title=About UHAA |publisher=UHAA |accessdate=2009-07-16}}</ref> It is headquartered at the University of Houston's on-campus Athletics/Alumni Center.  It was previously known as the "Ex-Students Association" and the "Houston Alumni Organization" prior to its current name.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ecommunications.houston.edu/uhclass/notice-description.tcl?newsletter_id=17638473 |title=Dean John Antel on the Jack J. Valenti School of Communication |publisher=[[University of Houston College of Liberal Arts and Social Sciences]] |accessdate=2009-07-16}}</ref>

